    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-01-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-01-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="542"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d542">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5731/75</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Secretary of State</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-01-25">January 25,
                            1934</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Minister of Norway<note n="2" xml:id="d542fn2">Wilhelm T. Munthe de
                        Morgenstierne.</note> called primarily to pay his respects and extend
                    congratulations on the successful meeting at Montevideo.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d542fn3">i. e., Seventh International Conference of American States,
                        December 3–26, 1933; see <ref target="frus1933v04#pg_1">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1933, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, pp. 1</ref> ff.</note> He stated that he
                    thought its stimulating effects would be helpful in Europe.</p>
                <p>The Minister again reminded me of his former suggestion that his Government would
                    like to negotiate a commercial treaty with the United States Government. He said
                    he had discussed the matter with Assistant Secretary Sayre who at present was
                    engrossed in like negotiations with other countries. I assured the Minister that
                    my Government was equally desirous of negotiating with his Government and that
                    as soon as our present negotiations were sufficiently advanced, we would take up
                    another list of nations or [<hi rend="italic">for</hi>] such negotiations, and
                    that I hoped we could include his government. I made no definite commitment,
                    however, and added that I would discuss the matter with Mr. Sayre.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>C[<hi rend="smallcaps">ordell</hi>] H[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                        >ull</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
